```

Copy this exactly for jq: it's the three-part contract you want — `HasParameter()` → `ParameterNotResolvedException`, `!IsFoldable()` → `InvalidInputException`, then `EvaluateScalar` + parse the filter at bind time (so jq compilation errors surface during query planning, not row-by-row). Note `InvalidInputException(*format_arg, "...")` — passing the expression yields better error location info than `BinderException`. Use `BinderException` when the rule is about the SQL surface (NULL not allowed, etc.); use `InvalidInputException` when it's the parsed value being bad.

The bind-data struct (`/Users/tim_vergenz/code/personal/duckdb-jq/duckdb/src/function/scalar/date/strftime.cpp:26`) is minimal:

```cpp
struct StrfTimeBindData : public FunctionData {
    explicit StrfTimeBindData(StrfTimeFormat format_p, string format_string_p, bool is_null)
        : format(std::move(format_p)), format_string(std::move(format_string_p)), is_null(is_null) {}
    StrfTimeFormat format;
    string format_string;
    bool is_null;
    unique_ptr<FunctionData> Copy() const override {
        return make_uniq<StrfTimeBindData>(format, format_string, is_null);
    }
    bool Equals(const FunctionData &other_p) const override {
        auto &other = other_p.Cast<StrfTimeBindData>();
        return format_string == other.format_string;
    }
};
```

This is your model: store the raw filter string for `Equals`/`Copy`, and the pre-compiled jq program object alongside.

